{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654974","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654974"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:57:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:57:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18642"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18642"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.52,0.12,0,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11374"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77773"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11374"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18642"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63290"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6906"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26387"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26696"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77773","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77773"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe posterior rectus sheath is an important anatomical structure of the anterior abdominal wall that has different compositions at different levels.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the composition of the posterior rectus sheath above the arcuate line?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transversalis fascia only","Internal oblique and transversus abdominis aponeuroses","Internal oblique and external oblique aponeuroses","External oblique aponeurosis only","External oblique and transversus abdominis aponeuroses"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einternal oblique and transversus abdominis aponeuroses\u003C/strong\u003E form the posterior rectus sheath above the arcuate line. This arrangement provides important structural support for the anterior abdominal wall.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransversalis fascia only\u003C/strong\u003E - While the transversalis fascia is present, it is not the only component above the arcuate line\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInternal oblique and external oblique aponeuroses\u003C/strong\u003E - The external oblique does not contribute to the posterior rectus sheath\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExternal oblique aponeurosis only\u003C/strong\u003E - The external oblique aponeurosis contributes to the anterior rectus sheath, not the posterior\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExternal oblique and transversus abdominis aponeuroses\u003C/strong\u003E - The external oblique does not contribute to the posterior rectus sheath\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBelow the arcuate line (located approximately one-third of the distance from the pubic crest to the umbilicus), all three muscle aponeuroses pass anterior to the rectus abdominis muscle, leaving only transversalis fascia posteriorly.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The posterior rectus sheath extends from the costal margin to the arcuate line and contains the posterior layer of rectus sheath and transversalis fascia.","Below the arcuate line, the posterior rectus sheath is absent and only transversalis fascia separates rectus abdominis from peritoneum.","The posterior rectus sheath is formed by the aponeuroses of internal oblique and transversus abdominis muscles above the arcuate line."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63290"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18642"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63290","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63290"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T10:17:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T10:18:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11374"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77773"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointesti